 the shift as evidence of the influence of communities on demographic behavior, and as an indication of the growing predominance of national over local communities. The author uses demographic data, too often the property of specialists, to examine themes of interest to historians, sociologists, economists, and political scientists interested in the integration of modern societies.Originally published in 1990.The Princeton Legacy Library uses the latest print-on-demand technology to again make available previously out-of-print books from the distinguished backlist of Princeton University Press. These editions preserve the original texts of these important books while presenting them in durable paperback and hardcover editions. The goal of the Princeton Legacy Library is to vastly increase access to the rich scholarly heritage found in the thousands of books published by Princeton University Press since its founding in 1905.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFertility, HumanzEuropexHistory. 0aNationalismzEuropexHistory. 0aRegionalismzEuropexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Legacy Lib. eBook Package 1980-1999z978311041344108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton Legacy Library eBook Package World Historyz978311041366308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140086121740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400861217423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400861217.jpg  a978-3-11-041344-1  Princeton Legacy Lib. eBook Package 1980-1999c1980d1999  a978-3-11-041366-3  Princeton Legacy Library eBook Package World History  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 